You're gonna have a finger puncture.

23:14.976 --> 23:17.020
All we need is a drop of blood.

23:17.687 --> 23:19.856
Been stuck so many times,
I got no veins left.

23:20.565 --> 23:22.025
Y'all are doing a good thing here.

23:27.406 --> 23:31.660
Hold on. It's... Excuse me. I'm sorry,
I just forgot something.

23:31.785 --> 23:32.786
Just one second.

23:45.507 --> 23:46.508
What are you doing?

23:47.467 --> 23:48.510
Get back in there, Edmond.

23:48.677 --> 23:51.430
Elizabeth, it doesn't work yet.
It's not even close to working yet.

23:52.431 --> 23:55.142
- It's not supposed to work. It's a trial.
- It...This...This isn't what I do.

23:55.225 --> 23:58.019
I... I work with machines.
I work with tech. I don't...

24:01.064 --> 24:02.899
How can we ask these people to...

24:07.529 --> 24:10.157
These people know
that they're participating in a trial.

24:10.282 --> 24:11.825
This is how these things are done, Edmond.

24:12.075 --> 24:13.160
This isn't you...

24:18.665 --> 24:19.708
Elizabeth.

24:27.632 --> 24:28.717
Go back in there.

24:51.156 --> 24:54.784
Uh, so, when you take this home with you,
just remember that...

24:55.994 --> 24:59.873
it's very, very delicate,
and so it can't be near a window,

24:59.956 --> 25:04.878
or an AC unit, or heater.
And... And it... and it can't get wet.

25:08.381 --> 25:09.382
Thank you.

25:24.564 --> 25:27.108
<i>You're back.</i>
<i>How was Nashville?</i>

25:27.609 --> 25:29.653
Good. Just unpacking.

25:42.457 --> 25:46.044
The patients know
